equation_narrative.headline: Polar representation shifts to positive charge prediction via late-layer lysine channels
equation_narrative.story: Through layers 1-23, the model assembles a representation of position 25 that oscillates between hydrophobic and polar character, reflecting its local sequence context (flanked by charged residues D24 and V26) and limited structural information (4 contacts, 1 co-evolutionary partner). The logit lens shows early dominance by hydrophobic residues (V peaks at 29% at L7, T at 41% at L6), but these reflect the representation's chemical character, not predictions. The transition to decision-making begins at L24-25, where polar-specific features activate. In layers 29-33, lysine-specific prediction channels emerge strongly: K rises from 10% at L29 to 31% at L30, driven by MLP neurons and attention heads that favor positive charge. The model ultimately predicts K (25.4%) over the correct answer N (20.4%), likely overweighting the charged local context.

perception_phase.summary: Layers 1-23 gather limited contextual information: 4 structural contacts and 1 co-evolutionary partner provide modest signal. Early layers (1-9) show high-projection attention features (F1:5480, F9:5728 with 45-60 proj) that encode general sequence context. The logit lens trajectory reflects shifting representation character: hydrophobic-leaning through L8 (V at 25%, T at 16%), then polar-leaning L9-23 (T peaks at 19% at L23, S fluctuates 20-22%). Layer 18 features (F18:6256 with 25.7 proj) mark a transition toward polar character. The representation remains ambiguous between small polar residues (T, S) and hydrophobic residues (V, L) through L23, consistent with the position's mixed local environment.
perception_phase.context_character: By L23, the representation encodes a position in a mixed polar/hydrophobic environment with charged neighbors (D24, K27). The logit lens shows T at 19.3%, S at 13.5%, and Q at 6.2%, reflecting a polar-leaning but not strongly constrained context.
key_information_sources: Structural contacts: 4 residues within contact distance, providing limited 3D constraint
Co-evolutionary signal: 1 coupled position, suggesting weak functional constraint
L9 attention features: F9:5728 (60.3 proj), F9:1281 (55.7 proj) encode sequence context
L18 attention features: F18:6256 (25.7 proj) marks shift toward polar representation
Local sequence: flanked by D24 (acidic) and V26 (hydrophobic), followed by K27 (basic)

decision_phase.summary: The decision crystallizes in layers 29-33. At L29, MLP neurons begin voting for specific amino acids: N29:4973 (0.64 proj) supports T/Y/N, while N29:5019 (-0.50 proj) erases S. Layer 30 sees a dramatic shift as K-specific channels activate: K jumps from 10% to 31% between L29-30, driven by attention heads (L29:10 writes 1.87 toward answer, L31:13 writes 1.79). MLP neurons at L30-31 show strong negative projections (total -3.48 at L30), creating volatility. The final layer (L33) resolves with attention-driven support: 11.0 delta from attention pushes K to 25.4%, narrowly ahead of N at 20.4%.
decision_phase.transition: At L23-24, the representation shifts from encoding context to activating prediction channels. Layer 24 features (F24:5080, F24:6677 with 15-16 proj) are the first with clear amino-acid specificity. MLP neurons at L24 show strong N-specific writers (N24:2823 with 0.52 proj, N24:554 with 0.42 proj), marking the onset of explicit prediction.

candidates.narrative: K emerges decisively at L30, jumping from 10% to 31% in a single layer. This surge is driven by attention head L29:10 (1.87 proj, structural writer) and L31:13 (1.79 proj, local writer). MLP support is mixed: L30 shows net negative projection (-3.48 total), but L29 provides 4.54 from MLP. The final layer sees strong attention support (2.21 delta) that pushes K to 25.4%. The model appears to favor K based on the charged local context (D24, K27) and positive-charge-specific features in late layers.
candidates.key_layers: Emerges L29-30, peaks at L30 (31.1%), final 25.4%
key_evidence: L29 head 10: 1.87 proj, structural writer (88% structural attention)
L31 head 13: 1.79 proj, local writer (90% local attention)
L33 attention: 2.21 delta toward answer
N29:4973 MLP neuron: 0.64 proj supports multiple polar/charged residues including K

candidates.narrative: N maintains steady support through the decision phase but never achieves dominance. Strong MLP writers at L24 (N24:2823 with 0.52 proj, N24:554 with 0.42 proj) and L28 (N28:2579 with 0.55 proj) provide consistent N-specific signal. N rises from 6.6% at L29 to 20.4% at L33, but is outpaced by K's late surge. The model's failure to select N suggests it underweighted the polar-amide character in favor of positive charge, possibly misreading the charged neighbors as requiring a charged residue rather than a polar one.
key_evidence: N24:2823 MLP: 0.52 proj, N-specific writer
N28:2579 MLP: 0.55 proj, N-specific with Q secondary support
N32:2150 MLP: 0.65 proj, strongest N writer in late layers
L18 MLP: 2.08 total proj with three strong N writers (N18:2880, N18:3216, N18:4400)

candidates.narrative: T dominates the logit lens in early-to-mid layers, peaking at 41% at L6 and maintaining 19% at L23. This reflects the representation's polar character during perception, not a model prediction. T is consistent with the small polar residues that fit the local sequence context. However, T collapses in the decision phase: it drops from 19% at L23 to 8% at L33 as amino-acid-specific prediction channels activate. The early T signal was a representation artifact—the model was encoding 'small polar' features, which project toward T in the logit lens.
key_evidence: L6 logit lens: 40.9% (representation character, not prediction)
L23: 19.3% (highest at perception-decision boundary)
N23:3152 MLP: 0.27 proj supports T (but also N and K)
Erased by decision-phase features: drops 11 points L23-33

candidates.narrative: Q emerges as a late contender, rising from 6% at L23 to peak at 16.5% at L31 before settling at 10.4%. Q shares chemical similarity with N (both polar amides) and benefits from some of the same MLP neurons (N28:2579 votes 0.40 for Q, 0.55 for N). Q's peak at L31 briefly makes it the logit-lens leader, but it loses ground in the final layers as K's channels dominate. Q represents the model's uncertainty between polar amide (N/Q) and positive charge (K).
key_evidence: L31 peak: 16.5% (briefly leads logit lens)
N28:2579 MLP: 0.40 proj for Q (0.55 for N)
N29:1619 MLP: 0.58 proj for Q, supports polar amides
Loses to K in final layers: -6 points L31-33

candidates.narrative: V peaks at 29% at L7, reflecting the representation's hydrophobic character in early layers. This is driven by local sequence features and the hydrophobic neighbor V26. However, V is not a serious prediction candidate—it collapses to 3% by L17 and remains low through the decision phase. The early V signal indicates the model was initially encoding hydrophobic features from the local environment, which project toward V in the logit lens but do not represent a prediction.
key_evidence: L7 logit lens: 29.0% (hydrophobic representation character)
L8: 25.4% (still high before polar shift)
Erased by L17: drops to 3.1% as polar features dominate
Final: 6.3% (minor recovery but not competitive)

turning_points.description: The representation shifts from hydrophobic to polar character. V and T dominate the logit lens at L6-7 (V 29%, T 41%), reflecting hydrophobic and small-polar features. At L8, attention head activity (key_velocity_events shows -1.44 delta) begins erasing hydrophobic signal. By L9, the representation has shifted: L leucine briefly leads at 32%, but this is still representation character, not prediction. This phase reflects the model reading local sequence context and structural contacts.

The perception-to-decision transition occurs here. At L23, the representation is polar-leaning (T 19%, S 13%, Q 6%) but non-specific. Layer 24 activates the first amino-acid-specific prediction features: F24:5080 and F24:6677 (15-16 proj) and MLP neurons with clear N-specificity (N24:2823, N24:554 with 0.52 and 0.42 proj). Layer 25 shows negative MLP activity (-0.87 total proj) that begins reshaping the probability distribution. The logit lens trajectory becomes meaningful as prediction rather than representation.

K's decisive emergence. At L29, K is at 10% and not competitive. Layer 29 MLP provides 4.54 delta toward answer, and attention head L29:10 writes 1.87 (structural writer with 88% structural attention). At L30, K surges to 31%, becoming the clear leader. This is driven by continued attention support (L31:13 writes 1.79, L31:18 writes 1.51) despite negative MLP activity at L30 (-3.48 total). The K-specific prediction channels dominate, overriding the N-specific signal that had been building through L24-28.

deep_dives.label: Early attention features L1-9
deep_dives.caption: Layer 1 and 9 attention features encode general sequence context with high projections (45-60). These are not prediction-specific but reflect the model reading local sequence patterns. F9:5728 (60.3 proj) and F9:1281 (55.7 proj) are the strongest context encoders.

deep_dives.label: Perception phase L18 features
deep_dives.caption: Layer 18 marks the shift toward polar representation character. F18:6256 (25.7 proj) is the dominant feature. MLP neurons at L18 show strong N-specific writers (N18:2880, N18:3216, N18:4400 with 0.34, 0.31, 0.30 proj), foreshadowing the decision phase.

deep_dives.label: Decision onset L24 features
deep_dives.caption: Layer 24 features are the first with clear amino-acid specificity. F24:5080 and F24:6677 (15-16 proj) activate prediction channels. Compare with L18 to see the shift from context encoding to prediction.

deep_dives.label: MLP neurons L24-28 (N support)
deep_dives.caption: These layers show consistent N-specific MLP support. N24:2823 (0.52 proj), N28:2579 (0.55 proj), and N28:1399 (0.51 proj) are the strongest N writers. Despite this, N loses to K in later layers, suggesting attention-driven override.

deep_dives.label: K surge attention L29-31
deep_dives.caption: Attention heads drive K's emergence. L29:10 (1.87 proj, structural writer) and L31:13 (1.79 proj, local writer) are the key events. L31:18 (1.51 proj, structural writer) provides additional support. These heads read charged local context and activate K-specific channels.

deep_dives.label: MLP neurons L29-31 (volatility)
deep_dives.caption: MLP activity is highly volatile in these layers. L29 provides 4.54 MLP delta toward answer, but L30 shows -3.48 total projection (strong erasers like N30:2797, N30:535). L31 is also negative (-0.50 total). The decision is attention-driven despite MLP resistance.

deep_dives.label: Final layer L33 features
deep_dives.caption: Layer 33 attention features (F33:2787, F33:9048 with 71.8 and 69.9 proj) provide the final push. The 11.0 attention delta at L33 is the largest single-layer shift, cementing K as the winner over N.

equation_narrative.resolution: The model assembles a representation of position 25 as a polar site in a charged local environment (D24, K27), with limited structural constraint (4 contacts, 1 co-evolutionary partner). Through L23, the representation oscillates between hydrophobic and polar character, reflecting ambiguous context. In the decision phase (L24-33), the model activates both N-specific (correct) and K-specific (incorrect) prediction channels. K wins due to strong late-layer attention support (L29:10, L31:13, L33 attention with 11.0 delta) that interprets the charged neighbors as requiring a charged residue. The model appears to overweight the D24/K27 charge context and underweight the polar-amide character that would favor N. The strongest evidence for K comes from structural and local attention heads at L29-31, while the strongest evidence for N comes from MLP neurons at L24-28 that are ultimately overridden.
